If this ever does happen...it won't be by the end of the month. Erdogan made a threat that it needs to happen by the end of October, but that's political theater. If EU agrees by the end of November, he'd agree as well. The issue is what is being done about the benchmarks and how far is Turkey from fulfilling them?: (Source) From the EU News Website: What is the state of play as regards visa liberalization for Turkish citizens?
As regards the implementation of the Visa Liberalisation Roadmap, the Second Report of 15 June 2016 described seven benchmarks that remain to be met:
1. issuing biometric travel documents fully compatible with EU standards;
2. adopting the measure to prevent corruption foreseen by the Roadmap;
3. concluding an operational cooperation agreement with Europol;
4. revising legislation and practices on terrorism in line with European standards;
5. aligning legislation on personal data protection with EU standards;
6. offering effective judicial cooperation in criminal matters to all EU Member States;
7. implementing the EU-Turkey Readmission Agreement in all its provisions. The Commission has encouraged Turkey's efforts to complete the delivery of all the outstanding benchmarks on the Visa Liberalisation Roadmap as soon as possible. The Commission and Turkey have continued an engaged dialogue to find solutions, including the legislative and procedural changes needed on all the outstanding benchmarks.
(End of Source) Of course, there is the sense that the EU does not want to allow Visa-free travel regardless of the benchmarks. I'd venture to say that not all EU members feel this way, but it seems reasonable some would.
